==================================
Simple Struct Serializer Generator
==================================

EXAMPLE:

////////////////////////
input
\\\\\

typedef struct data_t
{
  int count;
  int max;
  char key;
} data_t;

////////////////////////////////////////////////////
generated
\\\\\\\\\

static int SSS_read_data_t(FILE *f, data_t *s)
{
	if(SSS_read_i32(f, &s->count)) return 1;
	if(SSS_read_i32(f, &s->max)) return 1;
	if(SSS_read_i8(f, (int8_t*)&s->key)) return 1;

	return 0;
}

static int SSS_write_data_t(FILE *f, data_t *s)
{
	if(SSS_write_i32(f, &s->count)) return 1;
	if(SSS_write_i32(f, &s->max)) return 1;
	if(SSS_write_i8(f, (int8_t*)&s->key)) return 1;

	return 0;
}
////////////////////////////////////////////////////


program for generation C struct serializer
in files used little-endian binary format

SSSG guide:

1 step - set @SSSG tag and version in input file (and @SIZE tag + [<size>] if used array):
*always use unsigned version
example (data.h):

      // example triangle structure
      // @SSSG [1]
      typedef struct triangle3_t
      {
            float x;
            float y;
            float z;
      } triangle3_t;

      // use tag
      // @SSSG [1]
      typedef struct data_t
      {
            int count;
            int max;
            char key;
            triangle3_t triangle;

            triangle3_t triangles[10];

            int fixed_size_arr[32];

            // set size variable before array !!
            int size;

            // if it is array use tag and size
            int* dynamic_size_arr; // @SIZE [s->size]
            
            // if it is NOT array (just pointer to value) not use tag
            int *pointer_to_value;

            // dynamic structure support
            int tri_count;
            triangle3_t *dynamic_tris; // @SIZE [s->tri_count]

            triangle3_t *just_tri_pointer;
      } data_t;

2 step - write patterns:
recommended use patterns for simple types !!!
if 
use syntax:
      @s <structure field type> (patterns read since next line)
            (if just field)
                  SSS_$func_<value type, check sss.h from includes>(f, &s->$name)

            # no recommended - (if field is structure), check UPDATE 0.0.3!
                  #SSS_$func_<value type, check sss.h from includes>(f, &s->$name.subfield_1)
                  #SSS_$func_<value type, check sss.h from includes>(f, &s->$name.subfield_2)
                  #SSS_$func_<value type, check sss.h from includes>(f, &s->$name.subfield_3)
      @e (end tag on next line)

example (patterns.txt):

      # used i32 functions for int type (int can be not 4 bytes)
      # recommended use int32_t like type with fixed size
      @s int
            SSS_$func_i32(f, &s->$name)
      @e

      # no recommended since UPDATE 0.0.3
      #@s triangle3_t
      #      SSS_$func_f32(f, &s->$name.x)
      #      SSS_$func_f32(f, &s->$name.y)
      #      SSS_$func_f32(f, &s->$name.z)
      #@e

      # can be used type cast
      @s char
            SSS_$func_i8(f, (int8_t*)&s->$name)
      @e


3 step - run sssg:
$ ../sssg.py -i data.h -o SSS_data.h -p patterns.txt @i data.h @i ../sss.h @s 10000000
      -i = in flag
      -o = out flag
      -p = pattern flag
      @i = include flag (in example will be included "data.h" and "../sss.h")
      @s = max allocation size (for pointers and arrays) for 1 allocation (in example will set limit ~9.5 Mb)

4 step - use generated code:
in project include out file (example #include "SSS_data.h")

you can check /example folder:
      1 run build.sh
      2 run ./app and check like serializer work


UPDATE version 0.0.2
      add arrays support:
            1. fixed size array (example: int arr[10]; )
            2. dynamic_size_array (example: int *arr; )
      add pointers support (not recommended for use):
            1. example: int *ptr;

      array VS pointer:
            just use rule:
            array -> use @SIZE [<size>] in one line
            pointer -> not use any tags

UPDATE version 0.0.3
      add structure in structure support:
            1. example: triangle3_t triangle;
                  will be changed to SSS_$func_triangle3_t(f, s->$name)
                  like other patterns
                  ! but if you write the pattern for triangle3_t (like type)
                  will be used this pattern
      since this update:
            recommended use patterns for simple types (int, int8_t, float)
            for structures better use auto pattern generator